module AffineBorrow

(* The borrow idiom that fixes 07_affine_guard's affine error: the guard returns
   the value it inspected, so nothing is consumed twice.  The affine checker is
   satisfied — and under V1 the REFINEMENT checker still could not discharge the
   bound, because `b2` and `n` came out of a TUPLE pattern and V1 had no refined
   tuple components.  The two facts were true and the checker could not see that
   they were about the same buffer.

   This file is the THERMOMETER, and it has moved once per rung — 0 of 3, then 1,
   then 3 — which is what makes it a test and not a comment.

   V2.0 PROVED THE CONSUMER.  `size_of`'s contract promises `n == size(b)` and
   `size(b2) == size(b)`; the pattern `| (n, b2) =>` delivers both facts into the
   arm, the guard adds `n > 0`, and `take(b2, 0)`'s precondition follows.  That
   obligation — the one this file was written for — was discharged, and no further:
   checking `size_of`'s own BODY needs `size(Buf(n)) == n`, that taking a buffer
   apart and putting it back together does not change its size, and nothing in the
   logic said so.  The two goals left over were the two halves of one missing
   equation.  Refined products let a fact TRAVEL; only a measure can CREATE one.

   V2.2 SUPPLIED THE EQUATION, AND THE DIFF IS ONE WORD.  `size` below stopped being
   an `fn` and became the `measure` it always was — legal, because it is only ever
   NAMED in predicates and never called at run time — and the two halves arrive from
   the two hooks the rung is made of:

     Buf(n) in the body   the value it BUILDS is a term, so `size(Buf(n)) == n` is
                          instantiated at it and the postcondition is earned.
     | Buf(n) =>          the value it TAKES APART is a term too: the arm assumes
                          b == Buf(n), and the equation follows from that.

   Compare 05_buf_safe.lark, which is the same buffer, the same `size`, the same
   body — and leaves it an ordinary `fn`.  It proved what it proves at V1 and proves
   no more today.  The difference between the two files is not what the function
   computes.  It is whether the logic is allowed to know. *)

type Buf = | Buf of Int

measure size(b : Buf) : Int =
  match b with | Buf(n) => n end

fn take(b: Buf, i: {v: Int | v >= 0 and v < size(b)}) : Int =
  match b with | Buf(n) => n + i end

fn size_of(b: Buf) : ({v: Int | v == size(b)}, {v: Buf | size(v) == size(b)}) =
  match b with | Buf(n) => (n, Buf(n)) end

fn guarded(b: Buf) : Int =
  match size_of(b) with
  | (n, b2) => if n > 0 then take(b2, 0) else 0
  end
